@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{beki}}" grammar="@HI{{beki}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{beki}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<p>
<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}}(non-past) @HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} @HI{{desu}}
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{dearu}} @HI{{@EM{{beki}}}}
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{dearu}} @HI{{@EM{{beki}}}}
</ol>
</p>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} is an auxiliary that expresses the speaker's judgement that something should be
in some state.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} expresses the idea that something should be in a certain state because it is their
responsibility or duty, or because it is the right thing to do.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@KJ{{argument^sentence}}ha@KJ{{write}}ki@KJ{{straightaway}}su@EM{{beki}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    This thesis should be rewritten.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@KJ{{status*quo^attitude}}ga@KJ{{present^reality}}dearu@EM{{beki}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    This state should be the reality.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="past">@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}}</a> can be conjugated to express that something should have been done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{old*boy}}mo@KJ{{come}}ru@EM{{beki}}deshitayo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    You should have come too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="negation">@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}}</a> can be conjugated to express that something should not be done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{sonnnakotowo@KJ{{person}}ni@KJ{{say}}u@EM{{beki}}jaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    You shouldn't say that kind of thing to people.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="past-negation">@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}}</a> can be conjugated to express that something should not have been done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{he}}ha@KJ{{tie^marriage}}nankasu@EM{{beki}}janakattanda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    He shouldn't have married.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} can also express the idea that somone is expected to do something.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{suru@EM{{beki}}@KJ{{place}}ni@KJ{{scribe^mention}}ganai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    There's no description where there should be one.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} can immediately precede a noun.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{tale}}su@EM{{beki}}kotoha@KJ{{whole^section^tale}}shimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I told you everything I should tell you.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
Either @HI{{suru@EM{{beki}}}} or @HI{{su@EM{{beki}}}} is acceptable.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} should not be used to someone of higher status.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{beki}}}} is similar to <a href="grammar-mono-da.html">@HI{{mono da}}</a>
but the latter expresses a social norm (e.g. "Students should study")
and cannot be applied to a specific situation (e.g. "<em>You</em> should study.").
</p>

